{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_chinooksalmon_ver03/data/sn84020662/00414185940/1949051801/1260.xml":{"full_text":"THE NOME NUGGET\nPublished Monday, Wednesday and Friday by the\nNOME PUBLISHING CO.\nNOME, ALASKA\nTelephone: Main 125 P. O. Box 6i\u00ab\n$1.50 PER MONTH $16.00 A YEAR\nW. A. Boucher .Owner-Publisher\nEntered as second class matter October 14, 1943, at the postoffice\nat Nome, Alaska, under the Act of March 3, 1879.\nNome, Alaska, Wednesday, May 18,, 1949\nSPRING CLEAN-UP CAMPAIGNS\nNearly 10,000 American communities will join in ob\nserving Spring Clean-Up Week this year, the National\nBoard of Fire Underwriters reports.\nSome clean-up drives have already been held in\nsouthern cities, while others are just now being planned\nin many northern municipalities, as the drive moves\nnorthward with warmer weather.\nMobilizing Support\nFire chiefs, local fire safety committees, and public\nservice organizations are helping to mobilize public\nsupport for the drives, which receive the backing of\nmany civic organizations in each community.\nJudging by advance reports, more Spring Clean-Up\nCampaigns will be held this year than ever before. The\nfirst city-wide drive was held in Cincinnati in 1913.\nDrive Begins At Home\nThe campaign, which brings a substantial reduction\nin fire and health hazards each year, enlists all segments,\nof the community. Householders begin by checking\ntheir own homes for fire and health hazards, such as\nstacks of combustible rubbish, sooty stoves, frayed ex\ntension cords, and flammable liquids. Home inspection\nblanks which list these hazards can be obtained from\nthe National Board of Fire Underwriters, 85 John St.,\nNew York City. The Board also offers a special booklet,\n\u201cClean-Up\u2014Don\u2019t Burn Up!\u201d i\nA community clean-up campaign is another import-1\nant part of the drive. When vacant lots are cleaned and\ncleared, they provide safe and attractive playgrounds\nfor children in the neighborhood. j\n_\nTHE GRAVY TRAIN j\n(St. Marys, Pa., Daily Press)\nEvery country in the world with the possible excep-i\nlion of some in South America and inside the Iron Cur\ntain, is riding Uncle Sam\u2019s gravy train.\nSigning of the Atlantic Pact carried with it the im\nplication United States will have to finance arming of\nWestern European powers unable to carry their own\nweight.\nThe ink was not dry on the document before several\ncountries put in their bid for some of the many millions\nthat will be tossed around with wild abandon.\nSince the last shell was fired in Germany this coun\ntry has been Santa Claus to Europe to the tune of more\nthan 20 billion dollars. In addition to that we have un\ndertaken the Marshall Plan and all the billions it entails.\nIf the U. S. Senate confirms the Atlantic Pact it will\nopen another avenue of financial assistance to European\npowers impoverished by the recent war.\nThis will be in the nature of an arms program with\nweapons to be forged in this country and shipped over\nseas without a cent of cost to those lands who today sing\nsweet harmony with Uncle Sam whether it be basso\nprofundo or tenor.\nThe humanitarian aspects of the programs financed\nby the United States Treasury hold a definite appeal\nand on that score alone have been able to make legisla\ntive headway here.\nHere we stand, the youngest of all nations, the only\none capable of giving assistance to others. Here we like\nwise stand as the prize sucker land of all time. Propose\npensions for world war veterans and the resouding re\nbukes can be heard from here to China and back again.\nBut propose some measure to lend financial aid to\noverseas powers and it goes over with a bang, carrying\nvastly more financial outlay than pension plans to\nAmericans.\nWe are not carrying the torch here for pensions, but\nmerely to point out the different reception the two pro\ngrams receive here in America.\nRiding the gravy train at American expense has been\nKNIT ONE PULL TWO\nAUNT\nSAMANTHY\n\u00a7ii|SI|j\ngB.EL-AftCjiysi\nr\nI\nPOINTS OF OWENS ION\nh \u2014_\nquite popular over a long term of years. It began back\nin the First World War when we lent freely to various\nEuropean powers engaged in fighting the Kaiser and his\narmies.\nOf all the powers helped by American money at that\ntime, only Finland honored her obligations, even in the\nrecent war when through sheer force of circumstances\nshe was allied with Germany against Soviet Russia,\nthen in our loving embrace as a genuine fighter for de\nmocracy.\nWhen Uncle Sam had the collosal nerve to ask Eng\nland around 1920 for \u201cinterest\u201d payment on money\nloaned the British Empire, the reveberation was ter\nrific.\nUncle Sam was likened to \u201cUncle Shylock\u201d demand\ning his pound of flesh from a poor; downtrodden people,\nand none made more noise on the subject than Winston\nChurchill who spoke recently in Boston on the matter\nof common alliance between this country and the Brit\nish Isles.\nEngland has been the recipient of many billions of\nAmerican help through outright financial grants, or\nthrough lend-lease assistance. But in that respect she\nwas not alone. Other European powers are in the same\nboat.\nAs we bend an oar to help others stabilize their econ\nomy and get back on their feet, we should be mindful\nwe have serious and pressing obligations here at home\nto keep America out of her own poorhouse.\nI\nNO SERIOUS RECESSION j\nThe Bureau of Agricultural Economic^ which has a\ngood batting average on predictions, says that there\nwill be further declines in industrial production, prices\nand consumer incomes, but no serious recession is in\nsight.\nThe backlog demands \u201cthat carried over from the war\nyears\u201d have practically disappeared and the \u201ctremen\ndous demand\u201d for many consumer goods is slackening.\nHowever, no sharp drop in general economic activity\nseems \u201cto be in the picture.\u201d\nThe Bureau expresses the opinion that Federal, State\nand local governments will spend more money than last\nyear. It notes, however, that savings by consumers are\nincreasing although consumer-incomes will be big\nenough to support larger spending than in any year be\nfore 1948.\nReferring to the outlook for farm products, the Bur\neau says a decline in business activity will mean a\nweaker demand. Larger farm production would cause\nsome further price declines but \u201ca sharp, over-all de\ncline in farm prices is not expected.\u201d\nEven though a Medical School professor says that a\nman reaches his peak of physical efficiency at twenty\ntwo and then declines, it is encouraging to realize that\nthe decline is more gradual than the development.\n\u2014St. Louis Globe-Democrat.\nCONGRESS\nROUNDUP\n(Continued from Page One)\nthan usual.\nBy doing so, Mills figured, a\nprospective $3,000,000,000 deficit\nin fiscal 1950 could be turned into\n'a $1,700,000,000 surplus, eliminat\ning any need for a new tax bill.\nMr. Truman and his House lead\ners have picked ten major bills\nthey want the House to get busy*\non as soon as possible.\nThey are housing, labor, mini\nmum wages, lobby investigation,\ncrop insurance, federal buildings,\nAlaska statehood, rural telephone\nservice extension, pay raises for\ngovernment executives, and dis\nplaced persons.\nThis new lineup was decided on\nat a White House conference Mon\nday. I\nChairman Sabath (D.-Ill.) of the\nrules committee which normally\nclears bills for House debate .said\nhe expects most of them to get the\ngo-ahead within a week or so.\nYesterday the House was sched\nuled to debate a welfare depart\nment bill, but interest was cen\ntered more on an individual than\non legislation. The House was set\nto receive general Lucius Clay,\nback from his duties as U. S. mil\nitary head in Berlin.\nThe Senate was braced for a\nfresh round of debate on President\nTruman\u2019s spending program, and\neconomy advocates faced a major\ntest. Senator Green <D.-R. I.) has\nasked the Senate to reconsider the\nApril 28 action which sent the\n$2,400,000,000 labor-social security\nmoney bill back to the appropria\ntions committee with instructions\nto trim it five per cent.\nNext in line for Senate action\nare p.obably the appropriation\nfor the agiculture department, and\nthen the army department\u2019s civil\nfunctions money bill.\nI\nMuch Electrical\nPower Can Be Had\nFor Seward Area\nMA*) Special Washington Service*\nWASHINGTON, (>P) Harness\nj ing the Little Susitna River and\nI Cottonwood Creek in A1 a s k a\nS throughout 1948 would have pro\nduced more than 6,000,000 kilo\ni watt hours of electric energy, the\nI geological survey estimated yes\nterday.\nThe agency released a study by\nengineer W. Lawrence of the Lit\ntle Susitna River east of the Sew\nard meridian to a point a mile\nabout Archangel Creek, and of the\nCottonwood Creek basin.\nA diversion and conduit type of\npower development* Lawr ence\nsaid, could have produced a power\ncapacity in the 1947-48 water year\nof 636 horsepower 90 per cent of\nthe time and 4,100 horsepower 50\npercent of the time.\n\u201cBy diverting the flow of Little\nSusitna River to Cottonwood creek\nwith a system of dams and can\nals 960 horsepower could Have 4\nbeen developed continuously in\n1848, generating over 6,000,000\nkilowatt hours,\u201d the study added.\nA visitor at the Capitol was ac\ncompanied by his small son. The\nlittle boy watched from the gal\nlery when the House came to or\nder.\n\u201cWhy did the minister pray for\nall those men, Pop,\u201d\n\u201cHe didn\u2019t. He looked them over\nand then prayed for the country.\u201d\nMany a violin sounds as though\nits strings were still in the cat.","height":"27332","width":"20036"}}
